                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/3280.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Consul at Frontera</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Frontera</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-18T16:00:00-06:57">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 18, 1912—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>If I may circulate in the form of a circular letter the President’s proclamation,
                    dated the 2d March, relative to disturbances in Mexico, I believe it will create
                    an excellent impression among the authorities and all classes. The State is
                    entirely peaceful and Americans not molested.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lespinasse.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
